04452nam a22007575i 9780231525473DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2010    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315254737 a10.7312/lind130802doi  a(DE-B1597)459068  a(OCoLC)810931696  a(OCoLC)979574501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBM496.9.E4bL56 2010 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a296.1/25062221 aLindbeck, Kristen, eauthor.10aElijah and the Rabbis :bStory and Theology /cKristen Lindbeck. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Study of Rabbinic Narrative: Elijah, Folklore Studies, and Form Criticism -- t2. Oral-Formulaic Studies and the Culture of the Bavli -- t3. Elijah in Rabbinic Culture and the Wider Culture of Late Antiquity -- t4. The Three Generic Groups of Elijah Stories -- t5. Elijah from Rabbinic Times to the Twenty-First Century -- tAppendix: The Elijah Stories of the Bavli in Translation with Significant Variant Readings -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough an innovative synthesis of narrative critique, oral-formulaic study, folkloric research, and literary analysis, Kristen H. Lindbeck reads all the Elijah narratives in the Babylonian Talmud and details the rise of a distinct, quasi-angelic figure who takes pleasure in ordinary interaction. During the Talmudic period of 50-500 C.E., Elijah developed into a recognizable character quite different from the Elijah of the Bible. The Elijah of the Talmud dispenses wisdom, advice, and, like the Elijah of Jewish folklore, helps people directly, even with material gifts. Lindbeck highlights particular features of the Elijah stories, allowing them to be grouped into generic categories and considered alongside Rabbinic literary motifs and non-Jewish traditions of late antiquity. She compares Elijah in the Babylonian Talmud to a range of charactersangels, rabbis, wonder-workers, the angel of death, Christian saints, and even the Greek god Hermes. She concludes with a survey of Elijah's diverse roles from medieval times to today, throwing into brilliant relief the complex relationship between ancient Elijah traditions and later folktales and liturgy that show Elijah bringing benefits and blessings, appearing at circumcisions and Passover, and visiting households after the Sabbath.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/lind13080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231525473.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG